s://community.origam.com/t/how-to-order-data-records/3975\n\n@vikter (2025-02-26 10:18:44Z):\n   \n This guide demonstrates how to order data records in your tables or forms using default arrow control elements when their sequence is important. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/278dc805f3dfc4d91c5b5343f7d399dde1acc0d2.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for managing \u0022Status\u0022 entries in a data management system. At the top, there is a label \u0022Status\u0022 alongside a status indicator. Below it, UI controls are provided, featuring buttons for changing order (triangle icons), adding new entries (plus icon), and copying (clipboard icon). The table consists of three columns: \u0022Name,\u0022 \u0022Color,\u0022 and \u0022Order.\u0022 Under the \u0022Name\u0022 column, there are three entries: \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022In Progress,\u0022 and \u0022Done,\u0022 with corresponding color indicators showing light green for \u0022In Progress\u0022 and dark green for \u0022Done.\u0022 The apparent purpose of this interface is to organize and manage project or task statuses visually.\n\n\n  \n \n [!success]- Prerequisites for further work \n To follow along, you must meet the following prerequisites: \n \n  Running database server  \n  Running ORIGAM Server  \n  Project created in ORIGAM Architect  \n  Entity with fields created  \n  User screen created  \n  Running client application in your browser  \n \n Once these prerequisites are set up, log into the client application using the  username and password you created  during the project setup. \n \n In some scenarios, you may need to order entity data records and display them accordingly. For example, in a Task Manager application, the  Status  records follow a particular workflow, such as  New  \u003E  In Progress  \u003E  Done . \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ff543cdcda1d8253dab152bb428acff4d8f8dd3d.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface section titled \u0022Status.\u0022 It features a table with three columns: \u0022Name,\u0022 \u0022Color,\u0022 and a control area with icons for adding, removing, and copying items. The \u0022Name\u0022 column lists three statuses: \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022In Progress,\u0022 and \u0022Done.\u0022 Corresponding to each status, the \u0022Color\u0022 column shows visual indicators, with \u0022New\u0022 having no color, \u0022In Progress\u0022 represented by a light green shade, and \u0022Done\u0022 depicted in a darker green shade. This interface is likely part of a project management or task tracking tool to visualize the progress of different tasks or items.\n\n\n  \n While you might enter the data in this order initially, if you later wish to add a new status (e.g.,  In Testing ), you might want to position it before the final  Done  state, not after it. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b458179748546815d4f448c820db9b2cca53e0ab.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface section labeled \u0022Status\u0022 containing a table with columns for \u0022Name\u0022 and \u0022Color.\u0022 The \u0022Name\u0022 column lists four statuses: \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022In Progress,\u0022 \u0022Done,\u0022 and \u0022In Testing.\u0022 The corresponding \u0022Color\u0022 column features various shades: \u0022New\u0022 is represented by a light green color, \u0022In Progress\u0022 by a light green, \u0022Done\u0022 by a vibrant green, and \u0022In Testing\u0022 by a lighter green hue. Visible buttons above the table include \u0022\u002B\u0022 (add), \u0022\u2212\u0022 (subtract), a clipboard icon (likely for copy functions), and a blank space for additional actions. The apparent purpose of this section is to manage and visualize the status of tasks or projects.\n\n\n  \n To accomplish this, the most effective method is using the  OrderNumber  model property, coupled with a corresponding feature in the Client Application. Here\u2019s how to do it. \n   Model setup \n   Order field \n First, create a field in the entity whose records you wish to order. This field will store the correct order of each record. In our example, we create a field named  Order  for the  Status  entity. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/48f0f5a54d9114af3a40f1c4cef85c6110195ace.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Model Browser interface for a software application named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The left panel is organized into a hierarchical structure with categories including \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 and \u0022Entities.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:52:12"},"vector":[0.00077761995,-0.03420347,-0.0910276,0.010611274,-0.020119736,-0.0031557777,-0.041063566,0.0046829395,-0.004210766,0.033279885,-0.009180819,-0.0011374273,0.03909512,0.01711616,0.0220775,-0.0024726382,-0.019411748,0.01683971,0.013740698,0.019028055,0.0066404296,0.009460878,0.021060491,0.022766206,-0.012498049,0.04514436,-0.005672849,-0.026731843,0.006943638,0.0155,0.008159523,-0.03389766,0.011149255,-0.013414607,-0.02702593,-0.0050919726,0.011966082,-0.023821952,-0.04682206,0.014483845,-0.0058271433,0.015571568,-0.020555176,-0.0014859997,0.038297396,-0.024655327,-0.025338281,-0.009637165,-0.006106593,-0.06437775,-0.06304636,-0.010413481,0.029873926,-0.030106902,0.07080124,0.05792038,-0.06776575,-0.04142545,-0.039281875,0.027680008,-0.045921896,-0.00052856957,-0.0046634744,-0.020674009,0.005915128,0.030380953,0.027384292,-0.001466443,-0.0012541432,-0.050549816,-0.0022476222,0.03793328,-0.08344648,-0.020764634,-0.07318227,-0.00051012915,-0.002884123,-0.026659139,-0.030081257,0.006458354,-0.034469035,-0.011617417,0.012087931,-0.0039520827,0.01730765,0.015408755,-0.0058319685,0.085893005,0.026835904,0.04948468,-0.0051452327,-0.029578133,0.04282357,-0.04218861,-0.008926142,-0.0202